His POV is that we should avoid getting into features at the Friday meeting and stay in the high level space of how we're approaching reduction, modularity, and extend care's thinking of "beyond the match" to mean our thoughts around how people approach care, find what they need, etc etc (not just the things that happen after you match). Completely disagree. If we don't show significant progress with tangible features they're going to get frustrated. We're not going all the way to SF to tell them what they already know. Sheila wants vision. We can do a better job of framing it up in their language. But I strongly recommend that we stick to the plan.

That's my instinct as well - we might summarize our feature thinking with more vision less detail than our working sketches, but I think they're expecting us to give them some direction on what we're prototyping, and I think we need to get on the same page with Care so we can begin focusing on the design details, given that we're on a tight timeline.

Thanks for both of your input, it's incredibly appreciated. Ultimately what you both feel is best is what we'll do, and as long as we come in with a strong plan I think we'll come out looking good. I'm excited you're both feeling good about the plan! I'll keep pushing on the edges to make sure we're framing things up in their language and with our best foot forward, but sounds like, by and large, we're sticking to plan and can put some finesse into the framing.
